[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] In computer science, an **abstract machine** is a theoretical model that allows for a detailed and precise analysis of how a computer system functions.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] It is similar to a mathematical function in that it receives inputs and produces outputs based on predefined rules.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Abstract machines vary from literal machines in that they are expected to perform correctly and independently of hardware.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Abstract machines are "machines" because they allow step-by-step execution of programs; they are "abstract" because they ignore many aspects of actual (hardware) machines.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] A typical abstract machine consists of a definition in terms of input, output, and the set of allowable operations used to turn the former into the latter.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] They can be used for purely theoretical reasons as well as models for real-world computer systems.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] In the theory of computation, abstract machines are often used in thought experiments regarding computability or to analyse the complexity of algorithms.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] This use of abstract machines is fundamental to the field of computational complexity theory, such as with finite state machines, Mealy machines, push-down automata, and Turing machines.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Abstract machines are typically categorized into two types based on the quantity of operations they can execute simultaneously at any given moment: deterministic abstract machines and non-deterministic abstract machines.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] A deterministic abstract machine is a system in which a particular beginning state or condition always yields the same outputs.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] There is no randomness or variation in how inputs are transformed into outputs.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] In contrast, a non-deterministic abstract machine can provide various outputs for the same input on different executions.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Unlike a deterministic algorithm, which gives the same result for the same input regardless of the number of iterations, a non-deterministic algorithm takes various paths to arrive at different outputs.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Non-deterministic algorithms are helpful for obtaining approximate answers when deriving a precise solution using a deterministic approach is difficult or costly.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Turing machines, for example, are some of the most fundamental abstract machines in computer science.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] These machines conduct operations on a tape (a string of symbols) of any length.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Their instructions provide for both modifying the symbols and changing the symbol that the machine’s pointer is currently at.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] For example, a rudimentary Turing machine could have a single command, "convert symbol to 1 then move right", and this machine would only produce a string of 1s.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] This basic Turing machine is deterministic; however, nondeterministic Turing machines that can execute several actions given the same input may also be built.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Any implementation of an abstract machine in the case of physical implementation (in hardware) uses some kind of physical device (mechanical or electronic) to execute the instructions of a programming language.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] An abstract machine, however, can also be implemented in software or firmware at levels between the abstract machine and underlying physical device.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] An abstract machine is, intuitively, just an abstraction of the idea of a physical computer.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] For actual execution, algorithms must be properly formalised using the constructs offered by a programming language.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] This implies that the algorithms to be executed must be expressed using programming language instructions.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] The syntax of a programming language enables the construction of programs using a finite set of constructs known as instructions.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Most abstract machines share a program store and a state, which often includes a stack and registers.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] In digital computers, the stack is simply a memory unit with an address register that can count only positive integers (after an initial value is loaded into it).
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] The address register for the stack is known as a stack pointer because its value always refers to the top item on the stack.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] The program consists of a series of instructions, with a stack pointer indicating the next instruction to be performed.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] When the instruction is completed, a stack pointer is advanced.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] This fundamental control mechanism of an abstract machine is also known as its execution loop.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Thus, an abstract machine for a programming language is any collection of data structures and algorithms capable of storing and running programs written in the programming language.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] It bridges the gap between the high level of a programming language and the low level of an actual machine by providing an intermediate language step for compilation.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] An abstract machine's instructions are adapted to the unique operations necessary to implement operations of a certain source language or set of source languages.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] In the late 1950s, the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) and other allied organisations developed many proposals for Universal Computer Oriented Language (UNCOL), such as Conway's machine.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] The UNCOL concept is good, but it has not been widely used due to the poor performance of the generated code.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] In many areas of computing, its performance will continue to be an issue despite the development of the Java Virtual Machine in the late 1990s.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Algol Object Code (1964), P4-machine (1976), UCSD P-machine (1977), and Forth (1970) are some successful abstract machines of this kind.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Abstract machines for object-oriented programming languages are often stack-based and have special access instructions for object fields and methods.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] In these machines, memory management is often implicit performed by a garbage collector (memory recovery feature built into programming languages).
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Smalltalk-80 (1980), Self (1989), and Java (1994) are examples of this implementation.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] A string processing language is a computer language that focuses on processing strings rather than numbers.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] There have been string processing languages in the form of command shells, programming tools, macro processors, and scripting languages for decades.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Using a suitable abstract machine has two benefits: increased execution speed and enhanced portability.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Snobol4 and ML/I are two notable instances of early string processing languages that use an abstract machine to gain machine independence.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] The early abstract machines for functional languages, including the SECD machine (1964) and Cardelli's Functional Abstract Machine (1983), defined strict evaluation, also known as eager or call-by-value evaluation, in which function arguments are evaluated before the call and precisely once.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Recently, the majority of research has been on lazy (or call-by-need) evaluation, such as the G-machine (1984), Krivine machine (1985), and Three Instruction Machine (1986), in which function arguments are evaluated only if necessary and at most once.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] One reason is because effective implementation of strict evaluation is now well-understood, therefore the necessity for an abstract machine has diminished.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Predicate calculus (first order logic) is the foundation of logic programming languages.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] The most well-known logic programming language is Prolog.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] The rules in Prolog are written in a uniform format known as universally quantified 'Horn clauses', which means to begin the calculation that attempts to discover a proof of the objective.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] The Warren Abstract Machine WAM (1983), which has become the de facto standard in Prolog program compilation, has been the focus of most study.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] It provides special purpose instructions such as data unification instructions and control flow instructions to support backtracking (searching algorithm).
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] A generic abstract machine is made up of a memory and an interpreter.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] The memory is used to store data and programs, while the interpreter is the component that executes the instructions included in programs.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] The interpreter must carry out the operations that are unique to the language it is interpreting.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] However, given the variety of languages, it is conceivable to identify categories of operations and an "execution mechanism" shared by all interpreters.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Operations and data structures for memory management.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] An abstract machine must contain operations for manipulating primitive data types such as strings and integers.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] For example, integers are nearly universally considered a basic data type for both physical abstract machines and the abstract machines used by many programming languages.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] The machine carries out the arithmetic operations necessary, such as addition and multiplication, within a single time step.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Operations and structures for "sequence control" allow controlling the execution flow of program instructions.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] When certain conditions are met, it is necessary to change the typical sequential execution of a program.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Therefore, the interpreter employs data structures (such as those used to store the address of the next instruction to execute) that are modified by operations distinct from those used for data manipulation (for example, operations to update the address of the next instruction to execute).
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Data transfer operations are used to control how operands and data are transported from memory to the interpreter and vice versa.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] These operations deal with the store and the retrieval order of operands from the store.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Memory management is concerned with the operations performed in memory to allocate data and applications.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] In the abstract machine, data and programmes can be held indefinitely, or in the case of programming languages, memory can be allocated or deallocated using a more complex mechanism.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Abstract machine hierarchies are often employed, in which each machine uses the functionality of the level immediately below and adds additional functionality of its own to meet the level immediately above.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] A hardware computer, constructed with physical electronic devices, can be added at the most basic level.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Above this level, the abstract microprogrammed machine level may be introduced.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] The abstract machine supplied by the operating system, which is implemented by a program written in machine language, is located immediately above (or directly above the hardware if the firmware level is not there).
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] On the one hand, the operating system extends the capability of the physical machine by providing higher-level primitives that are not available on the physical machine (for example, primitives that act on files).
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] The host machine is formed by the abstract machine given by the operating system, on which a high-level programming language is implemented using an intermediary machine, such as the Java Virtual machine and its byte code language.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] The level given by the abstract machine for the high-level language (for example, Java) is not usually the final level of hierarchy.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] At this point, one or more applications that deliver additional services together may be introduced.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] A "web machine" level, for example, can be added to implement the functionalities necessary to handle Web communications (communications protocols or HTML code presentation).
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] The "Web Service" level is located above this, and it provides the functionalities necessary to make web services communicate, both in terms of interaction protocols and the behaviour of the processes involved.
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] At this level, entirely new languages that specify the behaviour of so-called "business processes" based on Web services may be developed (an example is the Business Process Execution Language).
[src:operational-semantics/abstract-machine] Finally, a specialised application can be found at the highest level (for example, E-commerce) which has very specific and limited functionality.
[src:operational-semantics/formal-semantics-of-programming-languages] In programming language theory, **semantics** is the rigorous mathematical logic study of the meaning of programming languages.
[src:operational-semantics/formal-semantics-of-programming-languages] Semantics assigns computational meaning to valid strings in a programming language syntax.
[src:operational-semantics/formal-semantics-of-programming-languages] It is closely related to, and often crosses over with, the semantics of mathematical proofs.
[src:operational-semantics/formal-semantics-of-programming-languages] Semantics describes the processes a computer follows when executing a program in that specific language.
[src:operational-semantics/formal-semantics-of-programming-languages] This can be done by describing the relationship between the input and output of a program, or giving an explanation of how the program will be executed on a certain platform, thereby creating a model of computation.
[src:operational-semantics/formal-semantics-of-programming-languages] Floyd published the paper *Assigning meanings to programs*; his chief aim was "a rigorous standard for proofs about computer programs, including proofs of correctness, equivalence, and termination".
[src:operational-semantics/formal-semantics-of-programming-languages] In 1969, Tony Hoare published a paper on Hoare logic seeded by Floyd's ideas, now sometimes collectively called *axiomatic semantics*.
[src:operational-semantics/formal-semantics-of-programming-languages] In the 1970s, the terms *operational semantics* and *denotational semantics* emerged.
[src:operational-semantics/formal-semantics-of-programming-languages] It has close links with other areas of computer science such as programming language design, type theory, compilers and interpreters, program verification and model checking.
[src:operational-semantics/formal-semantics-of-programming-languages] Apart from the choice between denotational, operational, or axiomatic approaches, most variations in formal semantic systems arise from the choice of supporting mathematical formalism.
[src:operational-semantics/formal-semantics-of-programming-languages] For a variety of reasons, one might wish to describe the relationships between different formal semantics.
[src:operational-semantics/formal-semantics-of-programming-languages] It is also possible to relate multiple semantics through abstractions via the theory of abstract interpretation.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] The operational semantics for a programming language describes how a valid program is interpreted as sequences of computational steps.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] These sequences then *are* the meaning of the program.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] In the context of functional programming, the final step in a terminating sequence returns the value of the program.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] Perhaps the first formal incarnation of operational semantics was the use of the lambda calculus to define the semantics of Lisp.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] Abstract machines in the tradition of the SECD machine are also closely related.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] The concept of operational semantics was used for the first time in defining the semantics of Algol 68.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] The first use of the term "operational semantics" in its present meaning is attributed to Dana Scott (Plotkin04).
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] What follows is a quote from Scott's seminal paper on formal semantics, in which he mentions the "operational" aspects of semantics.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] Gordon Plotkin introduced the structural operational semantics, Matthias Felleisen and Robert Hieb the reduction semantics, and Gilles Kahn the natural semantics.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] For a simple example, we consider part of the semantics of a simple programming language; proper illustrations are given in Plotkin81 and Hennessy90, and other textbooks.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] Let $C_{1},C_{2}$ range over programs of the language, and let s range over states (e.g. functions from memory locations to values).
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] Informally, the rule says that "**if** the expression E in state s reduces to value V , **then** the program $L:=E$ will update the state s with the assignment $L=V$ ".
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] Informally, the first rule says that, if program $C_{1}$ in state s finishes in state $s'$ , then the program $C_{1};C_{2}$ in state s will reduce to the program $C_{2}$ in state $s'$ .
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] Such a definition allows formal analysis of the behavior of programs, permitting the study of relations between programs.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] Important relations include simulation preorders and bisimulation.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] These are especially useful in the context of concurrency theory.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] Thanks to its intuitive look and easy-to-follow structure, SOS has gained great popularity and has become a de facto standard in defining operational semantics.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] As a sign of success, the original report (so-called Aarhus report) on SOS (Plotkin81) has attracted more than 1000 citations according to the CiteSeer [1], making it one of the most cited technical reports in Computer Science.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] Reduction semantics are given as a set of *reduction rules* that each specify a single potential reduction step.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] To get an assignment statement into such a position it is “bubbled up” through function applications and the right-hand side of assignment statements until it reaches the proper point.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] Since intervening $\mathbf {let}$ expressions may declare distinct variables, the calculus also demands an extrusion rule for $\mathbf {let}$ expressions.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] Most published uses of reduction semantics define such “bubble rules” with the convenience of evaluation contexts.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] where e denotes arbitrary expressions and v denotes fully-reduced values.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] Each evaluation context includes exactly one hole $[\,]$ into which a term is plugged in a capturing fashion.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] The shape of the context indicates with this hole where reduction may occur.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] This single reduction rule is the lift rule from Felleisen and Hieb's lambda calculus for assignment statements.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] The evaluation contexts restrict this rule to certain terms, but it is freely applicable in any term, including under lambdas.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] Felleisen showed that imperative extensions of this calculus satisfy these theorems.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] Consequences of these theorems are that the equational theory—the symmetric-transitive-reflexive closure—is a sound reasoning principle for these languages.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] However, in practice, most applications of reduction semantics dispense with the calculus and use the standard reduction only (and the evaluator that can be derived from it).
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] Reduction semantics are particularly useful given the ease by which evaluation contexts can model state or unusual control constructs (e.g., first-class continuations).
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] In addition, reduction semantics have been used to model object-oriented languages, contract systems, exceptions, futures, call-by-need, and many other language features.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] A thorough, modern treatment of reduction semantics that discusses several such applications at length is given by Matthias Felleisen, Robert Bruce Findler and Matthew Flatt in *Semantics Engineering with PLT Redex*.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] Big-step structural operational semantics is also known under the names **natural semantics**, **relational semantics** and **evaluation semantics**.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] Big-step operational semantics was introduced under the name *natural semantics* by Gilles Kahn when presenting Mini-ML, a pure dialect of ML.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] One can view big-step definitions as definitions of functions, or more generally of relations, interpreting each language construct in an appropriate domain.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] Its intuitiveness makes it a popular choice for semantics specification in programming languages, but it has some drawbacks that make it inconvenient or impossible to use in many situations, such as languages with control-intensive features or concurrency.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] A big-step semantics describes in a divide-and-conquer manner how final evaluation results of language constructs can be obtained by combining the evaluation results of their syntactic counterparts (subexpressions, substatements, etc.).
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] There are a number of distinctions between small-step and big-step semantics that influence whether one or the other forms a more suitable basis for specifying the semantics of a programming language.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] The main disadvantage of big-step semantics is that non-terminating (diverging) computations do not have an inference tree, making it impossible to state and prove properties about such computations.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] Small-step semantics give more control over the details and order of evaluation.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] In the case of instrumented operational semantics, this allows the operational semantics to track and the semanticist to state and prove more accurate theorems about the run-time behaviour of the language.
[src:operational-semantics/operational-semantics] These properties make small-step semantics more convenient when proving type soundness of a type system against an operational semantics.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] In rewriting, a **reduction strategy** or rewriting strategy is a relation specifying a rewrite for each object or term, compatible with a given reduction relation.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] Some authors use the term to refer to an evaluation strategy.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] Formally, for an abstract rewriting system $(A,\to )$ , a reduction strategy $\to _{S}$ is a binary relation on A with $\to _{S}\subseteq {\overset {+}{\to }}$ , where ${\overset {+}{\to }}$ is the transitive closure of $\to$ (but not the reflexive closure).
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] In addition the normal forms of the strategy must be the same as the normal forms of the original rewriting system, i.e. for all a , there exists a b with $a\to b$ iff $\exists b'.a\to _{S}b'$ .
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] A *one step* reduction strategy is one where $\to _{S}\subseteq \to$ .
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] A *deterministic* strategy is one where $\to _{S}$ is a partial function, i.e. for each $a\in A$ there is at most one b such that $a\to _{S}b$ .
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] Otherwise it is a *nondeterministic* strategy.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] In a term rewriting system a rewriting strategy specifies, out of all the reducible subterms (redexes), which one should be reduced (*contracted*) within a term.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] Stratego is a domain-specific language designed specifically for programming term rewriting strategies.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] In the context of the lambda calculus, *normal-order reduction* refers to leftmost-outermost reduction in the sense given above.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] Normal-order reduction is normalizing, in the sense that if a term has a normal form, then normal‐order reduction will eventually reach it, hence the name normal.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] This is known as the standardization theorem.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] Normal and applicative order reduction are strong in that they allow reduction under lambda abstractions.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] In contrast, *weak* reduction does not reduce under a lambda abstraction.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] *Call-by-name reduction* is the weak reduction strategy that reduces the leftmost outermost redex not inside a lambda abstraction, while *call-by-value reduction* is the weak reduction strategy that reduces the leftmost innermost redex not inside a lambda abstraction.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] These strategies were devised to reflect the call-by-name and call-by-value evaluation strategies.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] In fact, applicative order reduction was also originally introduced to model the call-by-value parameter passing technique found in Algol 60 and modern programming languages.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] When combined with the idea of weak reduction, the resulting call-by-value reduction is indeed a faithful approximation.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] Unfortunately, weak reduction is not confluent, and the traditional reduction equations of the lambda calculus are useless, because they suggest relationships that violate the weak evaluation regime.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] However, it is possible to extend the system to be confluent by allowing a restricted form of reduction under an abstraction, in particular when the redex does not involve the variable bound by the abstraction.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] For example, λ*x*.(λ*y*.*x*)*z* is in normal form for a weak reduction strategy because the redex (λ*y*.*x*)*z* is contained in a lambda abstraction.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] But the term λ*x*.(λ*y*.*y*)*z* can still be reduced under the extended weak reduction strategy, because the redex (λ*y*.*y*)*z* does not refer to *x*.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] Optimal reduction is motivated by the existence of lambda terms where there does not exist a sequence of reductions which reduces them without duplicating work.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] There are only two possible β-reductions to be done here, on a and on b.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] Reducing the outer a term first results in the inner b term being duplicated, and each copy will have to be reduced, but reducing the inner b term first will duplicate its argument c, which will cause work to be duplicated when the values of h and w are made known.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] Optimal reduction is not a reduction strategy for the lambda calculus in a narrow sense because performing β-reduction loses the information about the substituted redexes being shared.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] Instead it is defined for the *labelled lambda calculus*, an annotated lambda calculus which captures a precise notion of the work that should be shared.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] Labels consist of a countably infinite set of atomic labels, and concatenations $ab$ , overlinings ${\overline {a}}$ and underlinings ${\underline {a}}$ of labels.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] A labelled term is a lambda calculus term where each subterm has a label.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] The standard initial labeling of a lambda term gives each subterm a unique atomic label.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] Optimal reduction is then defined to be normal order or leftmost-outermost reduction using reduction by families, i.e. the parallel reduction of all redexes with the same function part label.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] The strategy is optimal in the sense that it performs the optimal (minimal) number of family reduction steps.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] A practical algorithm for optimal reduction was first described in 1989, more than a decade after optimal reduction was first defined in 1974.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] The Bologna Optimal Higher-order Machine (BOHM) is a prototype implementation of an extension of the technique to interaction nets.
[src:operational-semantics/reduction-strategy] Lambdascope is a more recent implementation of optimal reduction, also using interaction nets.
[src:operational-semantics/structural-operational-semantics] As a sign of success, the original report (so-called Aarhus report) on SOS (Plotkin81) has attracted more than 1000 citations according to the CiteSeer , making it one of the most cited technical reports in Computer Science.
